e Petricek -- t14: Trends and Issues in the Contemporary German-Language Short Story -- tAppendix: Contemporary German- Language Short Stories in Translation -- tRoman Ehrlich, “Engineers of Time” -- tSaša Stanišić, “The Factory” -- tSudabeh Mohafez, Selection of Short-Shorts -- tBibliography of Primary Texts -- tNotes on the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOffers readings of key contemporary trends and themes in the vibrant genre of short-story writing in Germany, Austria, and Switzerland, with attention to major practitioners and translations of two representative stories.Since the 1990s, the short story has re-emerged in the German-speaking world as a vibrant literary genre, serving as a medium for both literary experimentation and popular forms. Authors like Judith Hermann and Peter Stamm have had a significant impact on German-language literary culture and, in translation, on literary culture in the UK and USA. This volume analyzes German-language short-story writing in the twenty-first century, aiming to establish a framework for further research into individual authors as well as key themes and formal concerns. An introduction discusses theories of the short-story form and literary-aesthetic questions. A combination of thematic and author-focused chapters then discuss key developments in the contemporary German-language context, examining performance and performativity, Berlin and crime stories, and the openendness, fragmentation, liminality, and formal experimentations that characterize short stories in the twenty-first century. Together the chapters present the rich field of short-story writing in Germany, Austria, and Switzerland, offering a variety of theoretical approaches to individual stories and collections, as well as exploring connections with storytelling, modernist short prose, and the novella. The volume concludes with a survey of broad trends, and three original translations exemplifying the breadth of contemporary German-language short-story writing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGerman fictiony21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aShort stories, GermanxHistory and criticism. 0aShort stories, Germany21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aGerman Literature. 4aModern History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aGerman short story.  aGerman-language literature.  acontemporary trends.  aformal experimentation.  aliterary themes.1 aBartel, Heike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoa, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerstenberger, Katharina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerrmann, Leonhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerzog, Todd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKunzelmann, Heide, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamb-Faffelberger, Margarete, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarven, Lyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarven, Lyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcMurtry, Aine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcMurtry, Áine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewman, Rafaël, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlowman, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlowman, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPye, Gillian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoy, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https: